            <strong>🇬🇧 Thames Water may collapse</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Thames Water, the UK’s largest water utility, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-22-03-2025-wn1-3-faces-a-potential-collapse" target="_blank">faces a potential collapse</a> due to a debt crisis of approximately $25 billion USD (£20bn). A proposed emergency loan of around $3.8 billion USD (£3bn) currently under appeal aims to keep it afloat long enough for restructuring.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Ofwat, the regulator, warns that nationalization could cost taxpayers up to $5 billion USD (£4bn), while 12,000 pension scheme members risk reduced benefits. Thames plans to cut debt, appeal Ofwat’s cap on bill hikes, and attract investors. A court ruling on the loan is expected soon. Services will continue regardless of the outcome.</p>
