              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">Why are VC firms closing down?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/Dwindling-Investors-Market-Graph.jpg" alt="The graph shows the dwindling number of investors in the market" href="https://www.altdaily.co" />
             <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>The graph shows the dwindling number of investors in the market.</i></p> 
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Startups are staying private longer,</strong> delaying returns for VC firms. This forces VC funds to extend their investment cycles, making it harder to attract new capital.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Smaller firms struggle to compete, leading to market consolidation.</strong> Big VC firms like Andreessen Horowitz, General Catalyst, and Thrive Capital are attracting the most investments.</p>

 

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><strong>Example:</strong> In 2024, just nine VC firms raised over $35 billion, leaving smaller firms with limited capital. LPs (Limited Partners) prioritize proven firms over newer or smaller VCs.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Investors prefer backing big tech unicorns</strong> like SpaceX, OpenAI, and Stripe instead of riskier early-stage startups. This reduces funding opportunities for newer, high-risk startups, impacting smaller VC firms.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Rising interest rates have made alternative investments (bonds, private equity) more attractive</strong> than VC. This reduces the total amount of capital flowing into VC funds. Because of perceived safety, significant VC funds tend to get the lion's share of new money.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Institutional investors are more risk-averse</strong> due to macroeconomic uncertainties. Many pension funds and endowments are withdrawing from VC due to a lack of liquidity.</p>


        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>


