          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">Why is North Korea so good at crypto hacking?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/Amount-Confirmed-Stolen-By-North-Korea.png" alt="Amount confirmed stolen by North Korea" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Amount confirmed stolen by North Korea. Source: TRM</i></p>
        </mj-text> 
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">North Korea has emerged as a cyber superpower, pulling off some of the world’s biggest crypto heists. Here’s why their hackers are so dangerously effective:</p>  

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>State-backed talent cultivation:</strong> North Korea has long invested in training top math and computer science students, identifying talent early and funneling them into elite cyber units.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><strong>Example:</strong> After recognizing the importance of tech during the Gulf War, the regime began training talented math students in specialized programs, excusing them from annual countryside labor.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>National priority:</strong> Since the 1980s, North Korea has viewed cyber capabilities as essential to modern warfare and espionage. Cybercrime is now a major source of foreign currency.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><strong>Example:</strong> Kim Jong Un calls cyberwarfare “an all-purpose sword.” In 2023, the UN reported that cyber theft made up over 50% of North Korea’s foreign currency earnings, more than triple its exports to China.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Advanced social engineering:</strong> They’re skilled at phishing, impersonating recruiters, and <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-22-03-2025-f1-13-infiltrating-companies" target="_blank">infiltrating companies</a> by posing as remote IT workers.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>
          Example:</strong> North Korean operatives pose as recruiters and send infected files during fake interviews or get hired under false identities to gain access from the inside.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Bold and relentless tactics:</strong> North Korea isn’t concerned with stealth or diplomatic fallout, unlike most nation-states. Its hackers strike loudly, work around the clock, and show little concern for secrecy.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Top-tier crypto laundering skills:</strong> Their ability to “mix” and “chain hop” stolen funds makes them extremely hard to trace. Experts say they’re the most sophisticated crypto launderers in the world.
          </p>
